Assuming the `componentWillReceiveProps` you provided works with the component you have (it has the correct props, etc), then the following should replace it using `getDerivedStateFromProps`. 

```
static getDerivedStateFromProps(props, state) {
  // this is shorthand for if true (?), then do this action, else (:) do this action
  return props.errors ? { errors: props.errors } : null
}
```
`getDerivedStateFromProps` must be a static method. It takes current `props` as its first argument and current `state` as the second argument. It must `return` a modified object state or `null` (null escapes state updates). It&#39;s important to note that static methods won&#39;t have access to `this`. 

For side effects, like history updates, you should utilize `componentDidUpdate`: 

    componentDidUpdate(prevProps) {
      const { isAuthenticated } = this.props.auth;
    
      if (prevProps.auth.isAuthenticated !== isAuthenticated) {
        this.props.history.push(&quot;/dashboard&quot;);
      }
    }

**You have 2 options here.**

1. Rename the method. Which will work till **`React 17.x`**.

To rename the method, you can do this,
   ```
   cd your_project
   npx react-codemod rename-unsafe-lifecycles
   ```

   For more information read [this][1].

2. Another way is using `componentDidUpdate` method.
```
componentDidUpdate(prevProps){
   if(prevProps.auth.isAuthenticated !== this.props.auth.isAuthenticated){
      this.props.history.push(&quot;/dashboard&quot;);
   }

