Add a Subject called finalise to your component

    finalise = new Subject&lt;void&gt;();

and pipe a take until finalise before your subscription.

    this.companyService.getList(this.listOptions).pipe(takeUntil(finalise))

And add a ngOnDestroy

    ngOnDestroy() {
      this.finalise.next();
    }

This will clean up your subscription and cancel any outstanding http requests. You should do this with all subscriptions so you don&#39;t have any orphan subscriptions and memory leaks.

You could also take a look at a library I wrote to manage so of the http requests called ngx-rxcache. https://medium.com/@adrianbrand/angular-state-management-with-rxcache-468a865fc3fb

If I understand your problem correctly, everytime the user navigates to the next page, you fire a request to the backend to load that page. If they click multiple times on the next page button, this leads to multiple requests being fired in parallel, and the last one to return &quot;wins&quot;, i.e. those results will be displayed.

There are a number of ways around this. One - you could disable the navigation button in the UI until the latest request completes. This way the user would have to wait until being able to navigate again.

Also in the UI you could offer the user the possibility to jump to a specific result page, so that they don&#39;t have to click 5 times to get to page 5.

Another way would be not to fire the http request immediately upon a click, but to wait for a time instead to see if the user still clicks the button to get to a page further away. You would use `debounceTime` to delay the http request.

See the following example on how to achieve this: https://angular-s3qpgc.stackblitz.io

Your component would maintain a &quot;click queue&quot;, and place any button clicks into it:

    clickQueue = new Subject();
    pageNumber = 0;

    getDataAsync(): void {
      this.clickQueue.next(this.number++);
    }

You would subscribe to this queue with a `debounceTime(500)`, so that you only act once the user has stopped clicking for 500ms.
The `switchMap` operator ensures that, should the user begin clicking again after a request has been sent, the pending http call is canceled (and its results get discarded)

     ngOnInit() {
        this.clickQueue.pipe(
        debounceTime(500),
        switchMap(num =&gt; this.callService(num))
      ).subscribe(result =&gt; {
        console.log(result);
      });
    }

In my example, the `callService` function simulates the http call, which would return after a random time between 500-1000ms.

    callService(number) {
      return new Observable(subscriber =&gt; {
        setTimeout(() =&gt; {
        subscriber.next(number);
        subscriber.complete();
        }, 500 + Math.random() * 500);
      });
  }

In the example, you can see what happens when you click the &#39;Get data now&#39; button - which is what happens in your current case. As opposed to the &#39;Get data async&#39;, which uses debounceTime and switchMap, which would result in the intended behaviour.

**Final note**: As others have said, **everytime** you call `subscribe()` on an Observable, you must call `unsubscribe` at a later point as well, otherwise you are creating memory leaks and strange bugs in your application. That&#39;s another topic, you can check for example this article: https://blog.angularindepth.com/the-best-way-to-unsubscribe-rxjs-observable-in-the-angular-applications-d8f9aa42f6a0

